{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "I argue that Emilie du Châtelet's metaphysics of corporeal substance in the 1740s was a species of realism.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "This result challenges the ruling consensus, which takes her to have been decisively influenced by Leibniz, an idealist.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "In addition, I argue that du Châtelet's ontology of body is a mixture of realism and idealism, likewise non-Leibnizian.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "This, too, questions the scholarly consensus and opens the way for an overdue careful reassessment of her overall doctrine.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "I suggest that her view is best understood as dualism, a two-substance metaphysics that puts du Châtelet quite close to Christian Wolff.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "First, du Châtelet's basic metaphysics is a robust realism.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Idealist strands, while they exist, are confined to non-basic regimes.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "Second, her substance realism seems internally coherent, so her foundational project appears successful.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Historically, I show that du Châtelet's main source of inspiration was Christian Wolff; this goes against the widespread view that her metaphysics comes from Leibniz.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "Philosophically, I seek to highlight the explanatory power of some modern categories, like 'idealism-' and 'realism about substance.'",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "Leibniz's metaphysics reached du Châtelet heavily filtered, twice—first by what he chose to reveal to Wolff, then by what Wolff chose to keep from it.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "She was innocent of this fact, and so she thought she borrowed 'Leibnizian' doctrines, even as she relied on Wolff's heavy tomes for light; but the truth is markedly different.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "Documenting the sheer extent of Wolff's concepts and definitions in du Châtelet's tract will do much for my case.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "Du Châtelet's metaphysics rests on an account of being and its kinds.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "Du Châtelet anchored her view of substance in a theory of 'simple Beings,' which at times she also calls 'Monads.'",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "Du Châtelet's key premise is that body is a composite; hence, the 'properties of a composite Being' apply to it.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "Du Châtelet, moreover, asserts that a simple being has states, which 'depend on one another,' each on its predecessor, as the sufficient reason for why this state is 'actual, and why at this time' rather than another.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "Leibniz famously held that monads were 'windowless,' that is, causally inert in regard to one another.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "In his mature years, Wolff was not an idealist about substance; and he was a realist about inter-substance relations.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "Her basic substances are 'elements' equipped with physical forces, not mind-like unities endowed with analogues of perception.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU21": {
      "text": "Her bodies are real aggregates exerting transeunt causation, not windowless intentional objects engaged in self-action.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU22": {
      "text": "Examined on its terms, du Châtelet's metaphysics of material nature is a version of substance realism.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU23": {
      "text": "Her grounds of body are neither mind-like nor mind-dependent.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU24": {
      "text": "Though some details remain obscure, her view is realist, and so is her picture of bodies, which likewise exist qua real aggregates, without help from minds.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
  "relations": [
    {
      "source": "ADU1",
      "target": "ADU2",
      "type": "support"
    },
    {
